    "title": "Skill Building",
    "long_instructions": "##Using Formulas - Count If\r\n\r\nWhen trying to analyze our data, finding the count of specific elements can help us highlight certain features of the data.\r\n\r\n[Google Sheets Link](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1lg67vrIpnXaCe7P-XjqLmf6x91UcEvB-Ikw_rpqJDG8/view)\r\n\r\n**How many roller coasters were built before 1950?**\r\n\r\n**Do This:**\r\n\r\n1. Use the `COUNTIF` formula to specify the range.\r\n\r\n2. Then specify the criteria to determine which entries to count. \r\n",
    "teacher_markdown": "![](https://images.code.org/9a204b20b525e4f5272d2f49d9207cfd-image-1721836085919.png)\r\n\r\nExample student response:\r\n- There are 9 roller coasters built before 1950. I used the formula`=COUNTIF(K2:K158, \"<1950\")` to solve the question.\r\n\r\nOther questions students may wonder about and investigate include:\r\n- What is the average age of roller coasters in states with the most versus the least roller coasters? Or Do states with more roller coasters have a wider variety of coaster types? Or How does the intensity of roller coasters (as measured by speed, height, or inversions) compare across states with different numbers of coasters?\r\n- Whatever questions students investigate, they should be relevant to the dataset and its attributes. The insights they gain from any new graphs created should be directly related to the questions posed and supported by the data analysis conducted. They should be clear, concise, and logically derived from the data. Teachers should value insights that show unique thinking or new connections.\r\n",
